This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of visual odometry using deep learning techniques. It may also belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as visual odometry is an important component of robot navigation. Additionally, the use of deep learning models such as Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the use of deep learning models for sequential data suggests that it may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
